2) Normalization to 5000 reads per sample

Let’s normalize the original dataset by randomly subsampling 5000 reads in each station:

library(vegan)
## Loading required package: permute
## Loading required package: lattice
## This is vegan 2.3-1
otu_tb16_min5000_v2_t<-t(otu_tb16_min5000_v2)
otu_tb16_t_ss5000<-rrarefy(otu_tb16_min5000_v2_t, 5000)

length(which(colSums(otu_tb16_t_ss5000)==0)) 
## [1] 170

There are 177 OTUs that don’t show any occurrence in the normalized data. Let’s remove them from the table and take a look at its final dimensions:

otu_tb16_t_ss5000_no_cero<-otu_tb16_t_ss5000[,-(which(colSums(otu_tb16_t_ss5000)==0))]

3) General community analysis

3.1) Richness and evenness (Shannon index)

Most of the samples take Shannon Index values between 2.25 and 3.25:

3.2) Richness: OTU number

Lowest number of OTUs per sample:

## [1] 137

Maximum number of OTUs per sample:

## [1] 379

In most of the samples, we can identify between 200 and 250 OTUs:

plot(sort(OTUs_per_sample_16S_ss5000), pch=19)

boxplot(OTUs_per_sample_16S_ss5000, pch=19)

3.3) Index of evenness

3.3.1) Pielou’s index

pielou_evenness_16S_ss5000 <- otu_tb16_ss5000_div/log(OTUs_per_sample_16S_ss5000)

Most of the samples get values between 0.425 and 0.6, meaning that the numerical composition of different OTUs in a sample is relatively similar:

plot(sort(pielou_evenness_16S_ss5000), pch=19)

boxplot(pielou_evenness_16S_ss5000, pch=19)

The OTU_1 with 238811 reads, is the most abundant in the overall dataset:

head(sort(colSums(otu_tb16_t_ss5000_no_cero), decreasing=T), n=10L)

3.4) Abundance Models

3.4.1) Rank-Abundance or Dominance/Diversity Model (“radfit”)

The OTUs abundance distribution fits relativelly close to log-normal model.

3.4.2) Preston’s Lognormal Model

Preston’s lognormal model fit into species frequencies groups (we’re missing ~67 species):

otu_tb16_min5000_prestonfit<-prestonfit(colSums(otu_tb16_min5000_v2_t))
plot(otu_tb16_min5000_prestonfit, main="Pooled species")

veiledspec(otu_tb16_min5000_prestonfit)

3.6) Beta diversity

3.6.1) Dissimilarity matrix using Bray-Curtis index:

The index Bray-Curtis allows us to quantify the differences between samples according to the composition and relative abundance of their OTUs. In our dataset, most of the samples pairs take dissimilarity values between 0.25 and 0.5, meaning that their composition is substantially different.

3.6.2) Hierarchical clustering

The only relatively evident clusters we can distinguish in the dendogram stand out in the very left side of the plot. The central cluster ranging from samples MD256 to MD2156 could also be informative. TBD: assign Longhurst provinces information to each station.

3.6.3) Non-metric multidimensional scaling

We can identify a prominent group in the middle right side of the NMDS plot and a few isolated samples in the right edge of the plot. The stress parameter takes a value below 0.3 (0.1503428), meaning that the plot is valid.

plot(geo_distances_MP_16S_ss5000, otu_tb16_t_ss5000_no_cero.bray, pch=19, cex=0.4, xlab="Geopgraphic distances", ylab="Bray-Curtis dissimilarities")

4.1) Mantel correlograms

Mantel statistic is so low, meaning that the correlation between samples dissimilarity and geographical distances is weak; besides, it is not significant, so we shouldn’t consider the test meaningful.

mantel(geo_distances_MP_16S_ss5000, otu_tb16_t_ss5000_no_cero.bray)
